I am Rachel Cooke, the
senior communications manager

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:00.770
here at Khan Academy,

00:01:00.770 --> 00:01:02.850
and you are in for a treat today

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:06.570
because we have some
amazing conversation on deck

00:01:06.570 --> 00:01:10.200
with some two badass tech
chicks from Khan Academy.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:12.110
Super excited to introduce them

00:01:12.110 --> 00:01:14.250
and talk with them today.

00:01:14.250 --> 00:01:17.760
I wanted to say hello to our
international team members

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:21.143
in Brazil, Mexico, India, Peru.

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:24.760
Thinking of them, I
think that's it, right?

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:27.320
So hello to all of you
who are watching later on.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:29.970
Those of you who should
be sleeping, go to sleep.

00:01:29.970 --> 00:01:31.840
I wanna let everyone
know that you can submit

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:33.860
your questions on Facebook

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:36.190
if you have questions for
this amazing panel here.

00:01:36.190 --> 00:01:38.730
So we're gonna get right started.

00:01:38.730 --> 00:01:43.320
To my left, I have May-Li Khoe,

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:48.050
who is our VP of design
here at Khan Academy.

00:01:48.050 --> 00:01:50.290
She hails from great companies,

00:01:50.290 --> 00:01:53.043
like Apple, and LeapFrog, and IBM.

00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:57.083
We also have Marta, oops.

00:01:58.170 --> 00:02:00.220
Marta, I always forget
how to say your last name.

00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:01.500
Marta Kosarchyn.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:02.333
- Perfect.

00:02:02.333 --> 00:02:03.610
- Who's our VP of engineering.

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:06.360
She hails from HP and Intuit.

00:02:06.360 --> 00:02:07.760
And in case you don't know,

00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:11.280
Khan Academy is huge,
huge fans of Harry Potter.

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:15.230
So May-Li is representing
House Slytherin today,

00:02:15.230 --> 00:02:18.251
and Marta is representing
House Gryffindor.

00:02:18.251 --> 00:02:19.330
(audience laughs)

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:20.240
By the end of this chat,

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:22.240
you can guess which house I belong into.

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:28.000
So I'm a really big fan of
sort of classic movies, right?

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.040
And one of my favorite
lines comes from Casablanca,

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:34.330
which is like, in all the gin joints,

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:36.320
in all the towns, and all of the world,

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:38.050
you happen to walk into mine.

00:02:38.050 --> 00:02:41.773
So ladies, tell me what
brought you to Khan Academy?

00:02:43.710 --> 00:02:44.543
- Should I start?

00:02:44.543 --> 00:02:46.270
- [Rachel] Yeah, yeah.

00:02:46.270 --> 00:02:47.970
- What brought me to Khan Academy?

00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:52.590
Well, a long journey of many different,

00:02:52.590 --> 00:02:55.590
many different roles and
things through my life.

00:02:55.590 --> 00:02:58.580
Khan Academy is, you know,

00:02:58.580 --> 00:02:59.680
we've chatted about this,

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:02.600
just kinda I always say it
feels like full circle to me

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.450
because I started off studying math

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:08.630
and teaching math, finding
out sort of along the journey

00:03:08.630 --> 00:03:11.430
that I enjoyed teaching,
which I didn't think I would

00:03:11.430 --> 00:03:15.070
when I was being told that math education

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:17.180
was the only thing I
could do with mathematics

00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:20.590
as a girl, back in the day.

00:03:20.590 --> 00:03:22.040
And I was just a math major,

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:23.930
so I had to kinda make it anyway

00:03:23.930 --> 00:03:25.853
to find out I did enjoy teaching.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.030
Eventually found out I loved programming.

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:31.940
So the story kind of is

00:03:31.940 --> 00:03:34.850
I then worked in tech for over 20 years,

00:03:34.850 --> 00:03:38.050
and now full circle, I'm
back with Khan Academy,

00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:41.560
where I fell in love with
Khan Academy math videos

00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:42.660
because I could point to them

00:03:42.660 --> 00:03:44.840
and tell my friends, so there's this guy

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:47.570
who can explain all this
way better than I can,

00:03:47.570 --> 00:03:49.003
so don't ask me.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:50.673
- [Rachel] That's very funny.

00:03:50.673 --> 00:03:51.820
I remember when I told my mom

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:52.880
I was coming to Khan Academy,

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:54.040
I'm like, so there's this guy,

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:55.710
and she's just like, what?

00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:56.543
You're moving to California for who?

00:03:56.543 --> 00:03:57.376
And I'm like, no, no, no.

00:03:57.376 --> 00:03:59.204
It's Sal Khan, it's
legit, it's totally fine.

00:03:59.204 --> 00:04:01.720
(everyone laughing)

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:03.330
All right, all right.

00:04:03.330 --> 00:04:04.750
May-Li, go ahead, yeah.

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:06.810
- Yeah, also a long and winding road.

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:08.940
I studied computer science
and electrical engineering

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:13.930
as an undergrad and I
had wanted to study art

00:04:13.930 --> 00:04:16.890
as a high school student,
but my parents disapproved,

00:04:16.890 --> 00:04:17.840
and I thought at the time

00:04:17.840 --> 00:04:18.930
that I needed to do what they said,

00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:20.600
so I didn't study art.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:21.830
I figured I would study engineering

00:04:21.830 --> 00:04:24.530
and then go study art and do that later.

00:04:24.530 --> 00:04:25.450
But straight out of school,

00:04:25.450 --> 00:04:28.580
I insisted on trying to get a design job

00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:30.400
straight out of school
with an engineering degree.

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:31.810
So I went to the only company

00:04:31.810 --> 00:04:35.426
that let me design
stuff and then build it.

00:04:35.426 --> 00:04:37.540
So I could have those sorts of trade-offs

00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:39.440
with myself, which is hard.

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:41.150
But so we did that,

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:43.130
and then had a long journey
through other things.

00:04:43.130 --> 00:04:45.300
I think LeapFrog was another moment

00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:47.800
where I was kind of combining the design,

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:50.400
the engineering, and education.

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:53.150
Went on to Microsoft, Apple,

00:04:53.150 --> 00:04:54.620
and while I was working at Apple

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:56.490
on new methods of human input,

00:04:56.490 --> 00:04:59.170
I kept on prototyping things
that had to do with learning,

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:00.260
so I was like, let's play with this

00:05:00.260 --> 00:05:03.017
fancy new input device for learning.

00:05:03.017 --> 00:05:03.850
(Rachel laughs)

00:05:03.850 --> 00:05:04.980
And that happened so many times

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:06.260
that after a while I thought,

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:08.780
well, maybe I should
just focus on that part.

00:05:08.780 --> 00:05:10.280
- Right, that's amazing.

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:12.440
Yeah, I think, so both of you sort of have

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:14.910
these moments when you
were learning in school,

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:16.660
and you're just like you
had some kind of spark,

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:18.510
something kind of started in you.

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:21.040
And I think Women's History
Month is so important

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:22.360
because we get to kind of look back

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:24.410
at the pioneers and
people who have shaped us

00:05:24.410 --> 00:05:26.310
to kind of where we are today.

00:05:26.310 --> 00:05:27.590
And so for both of you,

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:29.274
is there a teacher or a pioneer

00:05:29.274 --> 00:05:31.360
that particularly has inspired you

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:32.883
to kind of go down this path?

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:35.400
- You start this one.

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:36.233
- Sure, I can.

00:05:36.233 --> 00:05:39.010
I'll start this one by, I do wanna think,

00:05:39.010 --> 00:05:42.380
somehow I subconsciously
found a lot of female mentors

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:44.690
in the department I was in.

00:05:44.690 --> 00:05:46.960
I don't think I realized I
was doing it at the time.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:48.730
I only realized it in retrospect, like,

00:05:48.730 --> 00:05:51.770
wait, how did I wind up with only

00:05:51.770 --> 00:05:55.690
female-identified advisors
in this major where,

00:05:55.690 --> 00:05:59.852
I mean, oftentimes that is
one in 60 kind of ratios.

00:05:59.852 --> 00:06:01.140
- [Rachel] Yeah.

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:03.100
- So Patty Maes who was at the Media Lab,

00:06:03.100 --> 00:06:05.220
who is at the Media Lab, Karen Sollins,

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:07.850
and Julie Dorsey were all
advisors of mine during that time.

00:06:07.850 --> 00:06:10.590
And I think I didn't realize I needed it.

00:06:10.590 --> 00:06:11.423
I think at that time I was like,

00:06:11.423 --> 00:06:13.170
no, I just got to power through everything

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:15.010
on my own, I don't need any whatevers,

00:06:15.010 --> 00:06:18.333
but actually I did and was
clearly reaching out to them.

00:06:19.382 --> 00:06:21.300
And then I think I've always been,

00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:23.670
I really got into both
programming and design

00:06:23.670 --> 00:06:26.430
because I was lucky to get
a Mac when I was a kid.

00:06:26.430 --> 00:06:28.050
And Susan Kare's work, obviously,

00:06:28.050 --> 00:06:29.883
has always really inspired me.

00:06:30.771 --> 00:06:32.470
I think as far as design work,

00:06:32.470 --> 00:06:35.220
there was recently a Charles
and Ray Eames exhibit

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:37.023
at the Oakland Museum.

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:39.230
Shout out to Oakland Museum.
- Eames chair.

00:06:39.230 --> 00:06:42.240
- Yeah, and Ray Eames' work is
also really inspiring to me.

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:46.180
Also very at the intersection
of science and design--

00:06:46.180 --> 00:06:47.540
- And Ray's the woman?

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:49.442
- And Ray is a woman, yes.

00:06:49.442 --> 00:06:51.630
(all laughing)

00:06:51.630 --> 00:06:52.463
- Important facts.

00:06:52.463 --> 00:06:54.130
- Important facts, yeah, we
recently heard somebody say,

00:06:54.130 --> 00:06:55.290
yeah, Charles and his brother.

00:06:55.290 --> 00:06:56.563
And we're like, no.

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:01.780
- [Rachel] And Marta, any pioneers,

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:03.770
teachers that have inspired you?

00:07:03.770 --> 00:07:06.060
- Yeah, well, all of the women pioneers

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:07.713
certainly have inspired me.

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:12.360
Again, sort of I harken
back to studying math first

00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:17.096
and just devouring histories
of women mathematicians

00:07:17.096 --> 00:07:18.463
because it was so rare.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:23.500
So that was always super inspirational

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:26.633
because they existed, which was something.

00:07:27.870 --> 00:07:32.550
And yeah, Grace Hopper,
certainly is inspirational.

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:35.560
I think the things she accomplished

00:07:35.560 --> 00:07:38.600
and also just a lot of her famous quotes,

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:41.447
like, "You don't manage
people, you manage things.

00:07:41.447 --> 00:07:42.660
"You lead people."

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:46.910
A lot of things that have
become philosophy for me

00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:49.350
as I've grown in leadership roles.

00:07:49.350 --> 00:07:51.880
So yeah, there's a lot of inspiration

00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:54.350
in the women who have gone before us.

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:55.183
- That's amazing.

00:07:55.183 --> 00:07:57.140
We're gonna come back to
your leadership style later,

00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:58.463
I promise, good questions.

00:07:59.590 --> 00:08:02.860
So I think for anyone
who's probably watching

00:08:02.860 --> 00:08:04.630
on Facebook or internet land,

00:08:04.630 --> 00:08:06.540
or watching here in the room,

00:08:06.540 --> 00:08:08.220
they might look at you and be like,

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:10.450
these two people have it all, right?

00:08:10.450 --> 00:08:12.780
They're super smart,
they're super talented,

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:16.163
they're in a dream job,
they're super gorgeous.

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:18.720
Could you tell me of maybe a time

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:21.117
where something like didn't go your way,

00:08:21.117 --> 00:08:23.020
and like how did you handle that?

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:25.060
Or maybe like a struggle,

00:08:25.060 --> 00:08:28.440
that those of us who are still
struggling can relate to?

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:29.323
Things like that.

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:31.560
- Yeah, for sure.

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:34.993
I think we probably both
have a lot of those stories.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:39.470
I guess one that's appropriate
to share today would be

00:08:42.540 --> 00:08:44.230
I remember the very first time

00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:47.063
that I was promoted
into a management role,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.420
a leadership role, a
managing leading people role

00:08:52.420 --> 00:08:54.820
as opposed to just an
individual contributor,

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:59.820
and at least three men came up to me

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:03.020
and said, yeah, you got that
job because you're a woman.

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:04.780
- [Rachel] Oh, no.

00:09:04.780 --> 00:09:08.410
- Which, as we know, if you're
an underrepresented group

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:10.350
in anything, how frustrating that is

00:09:10.350 --> 00:09:12.650
because the truth is
just the opposite, right?

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:16.540
So yeah, hearing those kinds of things

00:09:16.540 --> 00:09:18.010
and then saying these are my colleagues

00:09:18.010 --> 00:09:19.960
and these are folks
that I have to mobilize

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:21.990
and motivate and keep working with

00:09:21.990 --> 00:09:24.023
and stay positive, that's a challenge.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:26.440
- And so what did you do?

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:28.610
Were you just like, I'm
just gonna show them

00:09:28.610 --> 00:09:31.180
how talented, and how amazing,
just gonna do the work,

00:09:31.180 --> 00:09:32.703
or did you, what did you do?

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:37.090
- Yeah, you know, fortunately I was able

00:09:37.090 --> 00:09:39.090
to just say like, yeah, that's not true.

00:09:40.220 --> 00:09:43.560
I got this job because I was
the best person for this job.

00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:46.843
And yeah, just kept moving forward.

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:50.583
- [Rachel] Right, hater's gonna hate.

00:09:50.583 --> 00:09:51.416
- Yeah.

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:53.220
- [Rachel] And May-Li, what about you?

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:54.840
Tell us like a challenge, a struggle,

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:57.403
that you faced and kind
of how you overcame it.

00:09:59.170 --> 00:10:02.203
- Yeah, I was thinking
about that, it was funny.

00:10:04.424 --> 00:10:06.350
I think the way that we had talked

00:10:06.350 --> 00:10:07.870
a little bit about the
question, being like,

00:10:07.870 --> 00:10:09.427
well, when did you not get your way?

00:10:09.427 --> 00:10:12.400
And I was talking with my
partner about this last night,

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:16.035
and he said, "Are there times
when you don't get your way?"

00:10:16.035 --> 00:10:19.533
(audience laughs)

00:10:19.533 --> 00:10:20.473
I was like, yeah.

00:10:20.473 --> 00:10:22.470
I think the two things
that came to mind for me

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:25.563
were actually being turned down for jobs.

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:30.170
That definitely hurt.

00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:31.920
It's happened a bunch of times,

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:33.833
especially earlier on in my career.

00:10:35.938 --> 00:10:36.771
I think there's kind of,

00:10:36.771 --> 00:10:39.020
there's a couple things that I do.

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:42.740
One of them was I know
myself well enough by now

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:45.320
to know that I always
look back with gratitude.

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:46.500
So no matter what happens,

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:50.300
I know that I will have
a positive hindsight

00:10:50.300 --> 00:10:52.820
and feel like something
happened for a reason.

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:54.070
Whether or not that's actually true,

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:55.120
I mean, I don't know,

00:10:57.844 --> 00:10:59.180
but it feels like it happened for a reason

00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:00.013
'cause at the end of the day,

00:11:00.013 --> 00:11:00.880
I usually wind up being grateful

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:03.420
for the experiences that I do have.

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:05.680
I think another thing has been

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:08.540
just laser focusing on where

00:11:08.540 --> 00:11:10.143
I might need to learn something.

00:11:12.072 --> 00:11:15.080
And just saying like, okay,

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:18.170
well, were there actually
reasons behind this?

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:20.330
Is there something that
I could have done better?

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:22.270
And making sure as heck

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:25.213
that I've gone and filled those things.

00:11:26.336 --> 00:11:28.980
And so in the instances
that I have in mind

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:30.830
of being turned down after an interview

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:32.080
with a team or something,

00:11:33.280 --> 00:11:35.160
I know that like several years later,

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:37.250
the people that had doubted me

00:11:37.250 --> 00:11:38.770
were coming after me and saying like,

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:40.853
oh, I really need you for this project.

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:44.060
So that was like, okay, well,

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:46.560
I feel like I've filled
whatever that gap was,

00:11:46.560 --> 00:11:47.760
or maybe there wasn't a gap,

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:48.880
in which case, it's on them,

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:50.980
and they should just regret not hiring me.

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:53.270
- I kind of feel like both of you

00:11:53.270 --> 00:11:55.370
might be like a little bit sort of humbled

00:11:56.470 --> 00:11:57.970
about your career and
the challenges you faced.

00:11:57.970 --> 00:12:00.640
I don't think anyone sort of imagined

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:02.040
being a woman in tech might be

00:12:02.040 --> 00:12:04.640
the easiest thing to do, right?

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:05.480
There's certainly a lot of,

00:12:05.480 --> 00:12:09.870
sort of pot holes to
navigate, we'll say that.

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:14.870
So in your career, how have
you navigated those things?

00:12:15.030 --> 00:12:18.010
Like how do you sort of keep on the path

00:12:18.010 --> 00:12:19.010
that you wanna go on?

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:21.520
Like if you were like,
this is my end goal,

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:22.560
this is where I wanna get to,

00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:25.930
and I know that a career is
never just always upwards,

00:12:25.930 --> 00:12:28.607
but maybe you had to take some
