00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:14.900
what a great learner she is.

00:13:14.900 --> 00:13:16.720
She's always asking for like,

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:17.860
well, how do you do that?

00:13:17.860 --> 00:13:19.820
And can you teach me how to do that?

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:22.070
And one of the things
that I think we both do

00:13:22.070 --> 00:13:23.470
is we learn from each other

00:13:23.470 --> 00:13:26.250
and from all of our colleagues a lot here,

00:13:26.250 --> 00:13:29.493
which is what makes this such
an amazing environment for me.

00:13:29.493 --> 00:13:30.326
- [Rachel] For sure.

00:13:30.326 --> 00:13:33.061
- Because we just, kind of at that,

00:13:33.061 --> 00:13:35.610
you know, we're meta-learning all the time

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:37.990
in every way, yeah.
- For sure, yeah.

00:13:37.990 --> 00:13:41.200
All right, yeah, I think
the wonderful thing

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:42.370
about Khan Academy, I think,

00:13:42.370 --> 00:13:45.790
is like you have this
really amazing perception

00:13:45.790 --> 00:13:48.030
of the organization from the outside.

00:13:48.030 --> 00:13:48.947
And then you kind of come in,

00:13:48.947 --> 00:13:51.190
you're like, wow, this is really legit.

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:53.540
Like people are always trying to learn

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:56.070
and do better and improve upon themselves

00:13:56.070 --> 00:13:58.330
and it's always really amazing to me,

00:13:58.330 --> 00:14:01.340
sort of the caliber of human beings

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:02.910
that we have collected here.

00:14:02.910 --> 00:14:05.620
And so May-Li, any other war stories

00:14:05.620 --> 00:14:06.800
or anything that you'd like to share

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:07.950
from your career experience?

00:14:07.950 --> 00:14:08.783
- War stories.

00:14:09.660 --> 00:14:12.430
Yeah, I think that some
of what stands out to me

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:17.430
is just being in the environment
with such disproportion.

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:19.990
I had a long time in my career

00:14:19.990 --> 00:14:20.823
where I was the only woman

00:14:20.823 --> 00:14:23.560
and the only non-white person in the room,

00:14:23.560 --> 00:14:25.100
and whenever we had the larger meetings,

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:26.840
it was, again, goes back to almost like

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:31.250
during degree time when
it was 60 men and me,

00:14:31.250 --> 00:14:35.050
and just this feeling of
constantly having to prove

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:37.903
that I deserved to be there.

00:14:39.070 --> 00:14:41.660
I think some of the coping
mechanisms, just to share,

00:14:41.660 --> 00:14:43.830
one of them was I think when I was younger

00:14:43.830 --> 00:14:46.690
I tried to blend in and I tried
to tone down my femininity,

00:14:46.690 --> 00:14:49.490
and I tried to tone down
anything that made me stand out,

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:50.880
and at some point in time I realized,

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:52.640
and this is also as a designer,

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:57.593
that I should just enjoy
that and play it up.

00:14:57.593 --> 00:14:58.426
- [Rachel] Right.

00:14:58.426 --> 00:15:00.240
- And so I would go to executive meetings

00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:02.030
wearing all of the hardware,

00:15:02.030 --> 00:15:05.010
biggest earrings I could
find, tons of rings,

00:15:05.010 --> 00:15:09.460
and it was a lot of demos
that seeing my hands

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:10.640
and it was just like, no,

00:15:10.640 --> 00:15:11.680
you're going to get used to this.

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:12.850
This is the future,

00:15:12.850 --> 00:15:15.260
and we're gonna just style
it up and enjoy ourselves

00:15:15.260 --> 00:15:18.380
because I'm not trying to shrink myself.

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:20.060
So that was one.

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:22.680
And then also, just to
be super honest about it,

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:24.800
I think there are times when

00:15:24.800 --> 00:15:27.350
just some of the day-to-day difficulties

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:31.370
would be too much and I would go and cry.

00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:33.590
I had a place where I went to cry,

00:15:33.590 --> 00:15:35.040
and I think that's, you know,

00:15:36.013 --> 00:15:37.150
we can talk about it a
little bit more later,

00:15:37.150 --> 00:15:39.520
but for me, I think it's
very natural to cry,

00:15:39.520 --> 00:15:43.000
and I think it's a natural,
physical, healthy response.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.533
And so now if I have to cry,

00:15:44.533 --> 00:15:47.570
I just tell people, look,
water's gonna come on my face,

00:15:47.570 --> 00:15:49.300
we're gonna just keep
having this conversation.

00:15:49.300 --> 00:15:50.133
Everything is fine.

00:15:50.133 --> 00:15:51.860
This is like a natural physical response.

00:15:51.860 --> 00:15:54.170
Let's keep talking. (laughs)

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:55.120
- [Rachel] For the record, we're not just

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:57.130
like all sobbing here at Khan Academy

00:15:57.130 --> 00:15:58.797
during meetings.
- No, no, no.

00:15:58.797 --> 00:16:00.140
- Okay.
- No, this is part

00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:02.723
of my answer to the original question.

00:16:04.660 --> 00:16:06.073
Although it's fine to cry if you need to.

00:16:06.073 --> 00:16:07.893
- I mean, yeah sure, you can cry.

00:16:09.160 --> 00:16:11.650
Yeah, I think it's so important

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:15.070
for women especially to sort of understand

00:16:15.070 --> 00:16:18.010
amazing benefits of foraging your own path

00:16:18.010 --> 00:16:19.780
and being a pioneer in your own field,

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:21.570
wherever that might be, but also there's

00:16:21.570 --> 00:16:23.910
like real challenges and struggles

00:16:23.910 --> 00:16:24.920
that you have to overcome.

00:16:24.920 --> 00:16:28.120
And many of us aren't
given like a guide book

00:16:28.120 --> 00:16:28.953
of how to navigate it.

00:16:28.953 --> 00:16:31.460
It's kind of all a case by case basis,

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:32.753
and it sounds like both of you

00:16:32.753 --> 00:16:36.520
have kind of overcome a lot
of very different things.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:38.370
And I think, hopefully,
have come out better

00:16:38.370 --> 00:16:41.600
on the other side, so
that's very great as well.

00:16:41.600 --> 00:16:43.490
And so I guess from that perspective,

00:16:43.490 --> 00:16:46.440
what advice would you give to someone

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:48.560
who's coming up in the field now

00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:50.470
who is interested in a career in tech,

00:16:50.470 --> 00:16:52.010
or interested in being an engineer,

00:16:52.010 --> 00:16:54.430
or interested in being
an amazing designer?

00:16:54.430 --> 00:16:57.203
Like what advice would
you give them today?

00:16:58.714 --> 00:17:00.606
- Yeah, that's a great question,

00:17:00.606 --> 00:17:02.473
and often asked question, of course.

00:17:03.390 --> 00:17:05.470
And I always answer
sort of the two things,

00:17:05.470 --> 00:17:08.350
two pieces of advice that I share.

00:17:08.350 --> 00:17:10.580
One is, it's a cliche, but it's true,

00:17:10.580 --> 00:17:12.470
you have to be passionate
about what you're doing.

00:17:12.470 --> 00:17:14.140
If you really love what you're doing,

00:17:14.140 --> 00:17:16.010
if you're passionate
about what you're doing,

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:17.563
it shows in your work.

00:17:18.510 --> 00:17:20.786
It leads to success.

00:17:20.786 --> 00:17:22.477
And just believing in that

00:17:22.477 --> 00:17:24.350
and the fact if I'm passionate about it,

00:17:24.350 --> 00:17:26.220
I will get good at this,

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:27.490
even if I'm not good yet,

00:17:27.490 --> 00:17:28.700
and just sort of keep going,

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:31.573
to May-Li's point of
learning all the time.

00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:35.138
So I think that's important.

00:17:35.138 --> 00:17:36.880
And the second point I make

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:39.280
is actually related kind
of to the first point.

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:42.360
I think, for me, I learned
you have to be yourself,

00:17:42.360 --> 00:17:43.860
and you alluded to this a little bit

00:17:43.860 --> 00:17:46.250
just now, kind of with
style, and it's true.

00:17:46.250 --> 00:17:49.440
You have a style and you
can't become someone else.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:51.380
And I think respecting your style.

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:53.880
I can't tell you how many mentors

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:58.853
or folks have told me to add
a little gravitas to my style.

00:17:59.906 --> 00:18:00.739
- [Rachel] Meaning?

00:18:00.739 --> 00:18:02.003
- You know, just more,

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:06.370
May-Li's gonna do an enactment for us,

00:18:06.370 --> 00:18:08.284
I believe, at the end of this.

00:18:08.284 --> 00:18:09.767
- Stay tuned, stay tuned.
- We'll punt.

00:18:09.767 --> 00:18:10.660
- We'll punt on that for now.

00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:13.240
She's gonna give us a
physical representation.

00:18:13.240 --> 00:18:14.430
- I was told in my last job,

00:18:14.430 --> 00:18:17.900
like you need to be meaner, like, yeah.

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:19.530
- What?
- That was advice given to me.

00:18:19.530 --> 00:18:21.234
Like you need, yeah.

00:18:21.234 --> 00:18:22.090
- Yeah, maybe not meaner,

00:18:22.090 --> 00:18:25.425
but just maybe more serious and--

00:18:25.425 --> 00:18:27.260
- I was told point blank, right.

00:18:27.260 --> 00:18:29.150
- Yeah, just kinda.
- We're not gonna.

00:18:29.150 --> 00:18:31.250
- Yeah, so you have to be yourself

00:18:31.250 --> 00:18:33.780
because otherwise if you're
not your authentic self,

00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:34.790
I mean, you're not happy.

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:36.400
And the bottom line is
if you're not happy,

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:38.923
like you're not doing anybody any good.

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:41.878
- [Rachel] Exactly, exactly, yeah.

00:18:41.878 --> 00:18:43.430
- So.

00:18:43.430 --> 00:18:45.710
- Yeah, I think there's this thing

00:18:45.710 --> 00:18:49.020
that I've been telling a lot of people

00:18:49.020 --> 00:18:51.340
that when I get this question lately,

00:18:51.340 --> 00:18:53.150
and it's about confidence because

00:18:53.150 --> 00:18:54.803
I think a lot of people tell me,

00:18:55.640 --> 00:18:57.523
I can't do this because I
don't have the confidence.

00:18:57.523 --> 00:18:59.670
There's a lot of people really struggling

00:18:59.670 --> 00:19:01.110
with confidence and really struggling

00:19:01.110 --> 00:19:02.960
with what's called imposter syndrome.

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:07.180
So I have like mixed responses

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:10.200
and the imposter syndrome thing for me

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:13.800
really centers you as the
person having the issue.

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:15.940
Like you are the one
with imposter syndrome,

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:17.770
but it may be that you're
walking through this world

00:19:17.770 --> 00:19:20.680
constantly being given
cues from the outside world

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:22.450
that you're not good enough somehow,

00:19:22.450 --> 00:19:24.920
and yet, somehow we
like center that on you,

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:28.120
so that's like the reservation
I have about the term.

00:19:28.120 --> 00:19:29.750
- [Rachel] Oh, sure.

00:19:29.750 --> 00:19:32.000
- Because I think that
it's not just about you,

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:33.750
it's also about what surrounds you.

00:19:34.690 --> 00:19:36.460
So there's a dance there.

00:19:36.460 --> 00:19:38.910
The confidence thing, the
advice I give people is

00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:42.030
if you are a person who loves learning

00:19:42.030 --> 00:19:43.180
and loves doing new things,

00:19:43.180 --> 00:19:44.880
you're always gonna be pushing yourself

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:46.510
to be at that learning edge,

00:19:46.510 --> 00:19:47.830
which means that it's pretty likely

00:19:47.830 --> 00:19:48.920
you're gonna be doing something new

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:50.320
that you've not done before.

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:53.330
So it's natural to not necessarily have

00:19:53.330 --> 00:19:54.470
all the confidence in the world

00:19:54.470 --> 00:19:57.420
because that might actually
be false confidence

00:19:57.420 --> 00:19:59.320
because you are doing
something for the first time,

00:19:59.320 --> 00:20:00.580
and that's great.

00:20:00.580 --> 00:20:03.190
And so I tell people don't
worry about the confidence

00:20:03.190 --> 00:20:05.230
as a prerequisite, it's
not a prerequisite.

00:20:05.230 --> 00:20:06.730
You just need to be able to focus

00:20:06.730 --> 00:20:08.170
on problem solving so hard

00:20:08.170 --> 00:20:11.223
that you're not distracted
by your lack of confidence.

00:20:11.223 --> 00:20:12.056
- [Rachel] Right, exactly.

00:20:12.056 --> 00:20:12.889
- It can just stay there.

00:20:12.889 --> 00:20:13.840
You know, take it to tea,

00:20:13.840 --> 00:20:15.780
have a little conversation with it.

00:20:15.780 --> 00:20:18.120
But just be like you sit right there,

00:20:18.120 --> 00:20:19.780
we're gonna get to work
solving this problem,

00:20:19.780 --> 00:20:21.160
and you're not gonna stop me, that's it.

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:22.360
- That's really good advice.

00:20:22.360 --> 00:20:23.710
That's awesome.

00:20:23.710 --> 00:20:25.280
Kind of follow-up question to that is,

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:28.210
when do you both feel powerful,

00:20:28.210 --> 00:20:30.854
or how is it that you do feel powerful

00:20:30.854 --> 00:20:31.687
and kind of in those moments

00:20:31.687 --> 00:20:32.680
that you might be insecure,

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:35.290
or you may not be sure how to do things?

00:20:35.290 --> 00:20:36.793
How do you guys feel powerful?

00:20:38.500 --> 00:20:41.010
- Well, I believe that we take our power

00:20:41.010 --> 00:20:42.770
in just being ourselves, right?

00:20:42.770 --> 00:20:46.370
And recognizing thoughts of doubt

00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:49.390
as just thoughts.

00:20:49.390 --> 00:20:53.660
So I believe in

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:58.170
many Buddhist concepts in that area

00:20:58.170 --> 00:21:00.240
and just sort of being present

00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:02.190
in the moment of what's actually happening

00:21:02.190 --> 00:21:04.180
and realizing that a lot of the framing,

00:21:04.180 --> 00:21:06.380
which is where the doubts
or the confidence comes in,

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:07.680
they're just all thoughts.

00:21:07.680 --> 00:21:10.030
They're just neural transmissions.

00:21:10.030 --> 00:21:11.460
They're just thoughts and they can be

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:13.480
different thoughts at any moment,

00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:15.940
and there's only what's really there

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:18.383
and what's happening in the moment.

00:21:18.383 --> 00:21:19.560
And I think it's kind of the same thing

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:21.150
May-Li was saying, but it's true, right?

00:21:21.150 --> 00:21:24.090
I'm here, I'm focused, I'm
doing something, I'm learning,

00:21:24.090 --> 00:21:26.870
and yeah, the rest of it is a framing.

00:21:26.870 --> 00:21:28.810
And I could change that
framing at any moment.

00:21:28.810 --> 00:21:31.970
I can say, I'm really great
at this, I'm killing it,

00:21:31.970 --> 00:21:33.947
or I can doubt myself and say,

00:21:33.947 --> 00:21:35.640
oh, I'm really screwing this up.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:37.390
- [Rachel] Right, the first one's better.

00:21:37.390 --> 00:21:38.310
May-Li?

00:21:38.310 --> 00:21:40.330
- I feel like it's a bit of a pattern.

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:42.710
There's a book I really
like called Art &amp; Fear,

00:21:42.710 --> 00:21:45.043
and what it talks about
is that as an artist

00:21:45.043 --> 00:21:48.310
or anybody that's pushing
yourself on your edge,

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:50.470
your bar or your standard for yourself

00:21:50.470 --> 00:21:52.290
has continued to rise
because you learn more,

00:21:52.290 --> 00:21:53.700
and so you never meet your own standard

00:21:53.700 --> 00:21:56.160
because your standard moves
up as your skill moves up.

00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:58.050
And so all I've done is basically like,

00:21:58.050 --> 00:22:01.880
I have these, I talk
myself out of anything

00:22:01.880 --> 00:22:02.740
that might be paralyzing.

00:22:02.740 --> 00:22:04.050
I'll be like, okay, well,
have you done something

00:22:04.050 --> 00:22:05.820
you don't know how to do before, yes.

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:07.310
Did it come out okay,
yes, it came out okay.

00:22:07.310 --> 00:22:08.540
Just like take a deep breath,

00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:11.090
count to three, do it anyway. (laughs)

00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:13.300
- That's also pretty solid advice, yeah.

00:22:13.300 --> 00:22:14.133
I love that.

00:22:14.133 --> 00:22:16.920
So we have some really great philosophies,

00:22:16.920 --> 00:22:19.010
some Buddhist teachings.

00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:21.440
My power move is listening
to our Cardi B tracks.

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:23.890
So you know, different
strokes for different folks.

00:22:23.890 --> 00:22:24.740
Whatever works for you.

00:22:24.740 --> 00:22:26.240
I love it.
- Musical as hell.

