00:25:08.019 --> 00:25:11.960
in an engineering
organization, for example.

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:14.320
So I think the pace has been slower

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:17.270
than maybe we thought, say, 20 years ago

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:19.343
when we saw things changing a little bit.

00:25:20.320 --> 00:25:22.150
So yeah, I come back to there's still

00:25:22.150 --> 00:25:23.000
a lot of work to do,

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.380
so none of us should be
complacent about that.

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:26.213
- [Rachel] That's true.

00:25:26.213 --> 00:25:27.046
- You got to always celebrate.

00:25:27.046 --> 00:25:27.879
- Still more work to do,

00:25:27.879 --> 00:25:29.820
but I think we're all kind of hopeful

00:25:29.820 --> 00:25:31.590
of where things are going, I think.

00:25:31.590 --> 00:25:32.770
So definitely, the industry's having

00:25:32.770 --> 00:25:34.210
a lot of good conversations,

00:25:34.210 --> 00:25:36.530
and I think more people trying
to hold them accountable

00:25:36.530 --> 00:25:37.880
to sort of be more representative

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:39.660
of the society in which it serves.

00:25:39.660 --> 00:25:41.630
So I think that's great.

00:25:41.630 --> 00:25:44.120
And Marta, you spoke about earlier

00:25:44.120 --> 00:25:47.230
about when you became a manager

00:25:47.230 --> 00:25:48.391
and sort of how hard that was

00:25:48.391 --> 00:25:51.150
for people who are maybe
a little bit reluctant.

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:52.890
And I can imagine for both of you

00:25:52.890 --> 00:25:55.830
that you didn't really have many

00:25:55.830 --> 00:25:58.310
female managers or leaders

00:25:58.310 --> 00:26:00.930
as you were coming up in this industry.

00:26:00.930 --> 00:26:03.930
How is it that you developed
your own leadership style

00:26:03.930 --> 00:26:05.830
or management style when perhaps

00:26:05.830 --> 00:26:08.563
you didn't have those kind
of role models to go to?

00:26:10.170 --> 00:26:13.410
- Yeah, that's a great question
and definitely emphasis

00:26:13.410 --> 00:26:14.890
on the word how did you develop it

00:26:14.890 --> 00:26:16.690
because it's still a work in progress.

00:26:16.690 --> 00:26:18.157
- It's still a work in a progress.

00:26:18.157 --> 00:26:18.997
- Still a work in progress

00:26:18.997 --> 00:26:21.513
and we're developing all the time, I hope.

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:24.260
But you're right, I mean, it's not like

00:26:24.260 --> 00:26:26.780
you could see a cookie
cutter cardboard cutout

00:26:26.780 --> 00:26:29.000
and say, yeah, I wanna be like so-and-so

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:33.763
because so-and-so didn't
resemble me in any way.

00:26:35.090 --> 00:26:40.090
So yeah, becoming a leader is hard,

00:26:40.830 --> 00:26:43.990
stepping into roles of leading
people is incredibly hard.

00:26:43.990 --> 00:26:46.710
It looks so much easier than it is.

00:26:46.710 --> 00:26:47.900
I mean, that's one of those things

00:26:47.900 --> 00:26:50.640
that I think everybody who's
become a first-time manager

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:52.850
or first-time leader thinks like,

00:26:52.850 --> 00:26:55.300
oh, I'm gonna have that people part down

00:26:55.300 --> 00:26:57.720
'cause I'm a people
person and I love people.

00:26:57.720 --> 00:26:59.570
You know, it's everything
else that'll be a struggle,

00:26:59.570 --> 00:27:02.550
and I think we all find out, oh boy,

00:27:02.550 --> 00:27:04.550
no, is that not the case.

00:27:04.550 --> 00:27:08.090
Actually helping my folks grow,

00:27:08.090 --> 00:27:12.040
and yet leading and leading from the front

00:27:12.040 --> 00:27:15.680
and eventually you learn that's like

00:27:15.680 --> 00:27:17.560
you're at the front
for all the hard stuff,

00:27:17.560 --> 00:27:19.500
and you're at the back
for all the easy stuff,

00:27:19.500 --> 00:27:23.550
and yeah, but it's a work
in progress, for sure.

00:27:23.550 --> 00:27:27.100
And seeking out other women from all kinds

00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:30.457
of functions, for me, in the working world

00:27:30.457 --> 00:27:32.980
has been super helpful when there

00:27:32.980 --> 00:27:36.273
weren't role models in
engineering, for example.

00:27:37.495 --> 00:27:39.120
I think that's a good strategy.

00:27:39.120 --> 00:27:40.500
- Do you have like a managing tip

00:27:40.500 --> 00:27:41.333
that you would give someone,

00:27:41.333 --> 00:27:42.330
or like something that you learn,

00:27:42.330 --> 00:27:43.420
and you're like, oh, this is it.

00:27:43.420 --> 00:27:46.473
This is a key to unlocking
management style.

00:27:47.970 --> 00:27:50.161
- Are you looking for one
of my mantras, Rachel?

00:27:50.161 --> 00:27:50.994
(everyone laughing)

00:27:50.994 --> 00:27:51.960
- [Rachel] I am always looking for

00:27:51.960 --> 00:27:55.840
one of your Marta mantras, Marta mantras.

00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:56.887
We're just gonna do--

00:27:56.887 --> 00:27:58.190
- Marta's mantras--

00:27:58.190 --> 00:28:00.483
- One of my mantras is no surprises.

00:28:01.550 --> 00:28:03.080
That's what I try to teach everyone

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:06.340
is we can deal with anything,
we can fix anything,

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:09.350
we can adjust to anything
and we'll succeed,

00:28:09.350 --> 00:28:11.900
just please tell me as soon
as you know about that.

00:28:13.240 --> 00:28:15.870
- [Rachel] No surprises,
all right, excellent.

00:28:15.870 --> 00:28:18.443
- I think one of the things for me,

00:28:19.426 --> 00:28:20.620
and this is something I noticed

00:28:20.620 --> 00:28:22.330
when I had a former director

00:28:22.330 --> 00:28:25.390
who was surprised when she realized

00:28:28.461 --> 00:28:30.580
that she needed to adjust things

00:28:30.580 --> 00:28:33.770
so that people didn't have
to fight as hard as she did.

00:28:33.770 --> 00:28:35.850
And I think that's one of the things

00:28:35.850 --> 00:28:38.260
that it takes an extra step to realize,

00:28:38.260 --> 00:28:41.030
like just because I'm here doesn't mean

00:28:41.030 --> 00:28:42.530
that everybody else should go through

00:28:42.530 --> 00:28:44.340
what I had to go through to get here.

00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:46.470
So what is it that I need to change?

00:28:46.470 --> 00:28:49.010
And just like putting that
extra layer of thought

00:28:49.010 --> 00:28:50.310
on top of things all the time

00:28:50.310 --> 00:28:52.640
and double checking everything to say,

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:55.050
okay, am I expecting this
because this is status quo?

00:28:55.050 --> 00:28:57.693
Or is this something
that really should shift?

00:28:59.200 --> 00:29:02.023
So that's just like an extra
layer on top of everything.

00:29:03.490 --> 00:29:06.313
Yeah, it takes like two
layers of thought, yeah.

00:29:07.180 --> 00:29:08.013
- [Rachel] Do you have a--

00:29:08.013 --> 00:29:10.290
- Constant self-check, yeah.

00:29:10.290 --> 00:29:12.060
- And in that self-check,

00:29:12.060 --> 00:29:13.260
are you thinking more of like,

00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:16.990
I want to sort of make my decision making

00:29:16.990 --> 00:29:19.710
and leadership more inclusive?

00:29:19.710 --> 00:29:22.300
Or are you thinking I'm,

00:29:22.300 --> 00:29:25.540
or are you intentionally trying
to shake up the status quo?

00:29:25.540 --> 00:29:29.810
Are you kind of in your
own management role,

00:29:29.810 --> 00:29:32.380
are you thinking, I'm
not gonna do it that way

00:29:32.380 --> 00:29:34.280
because it shouldn't be done that way?

00:29:35.760 --> 00:29:37.350
- Yeah, I think I'm really focused

00:29:37.350 --> 00:29:41.480
on trying to build systems so that people

00:29:41.480 --> 00:29:44.088
aren't systematically shut out.

00:29:44.088 --> 00:29:48.270
So a really simple
example, airtime, right?

00:29:48.270 --> 00:29:49.860
Fighting for airtime in a meeting,

00:29:49.860 --> 00:29:51.830
that's a thing that oftentimes happens.

00:29:51.830 --> 00:29:53.900
And so what we do on the design team

00:29:53.900 --> 00:29:57.290
is we will switch to non-synchronous

00:29:57.290 --> 00:29:59.090
verbal communication 'cause we use,

00:29:59.090 --> 00:30:00.500
we have a lot of remote
people at Khan Academy,

00:30:00.500 --> 00:30:01.970
so we use a lot of docs,

00:30:01.970 --> 00:30:04.420
design team's using Figma now,

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:05.530
and we use Google Docs,

00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:06.920
so sometimes we'll say, you know what?

00:30:06.920 --> 00:30:08.230
Let's do a quick brainstorm.

00:30:08.230 --> 00:30:09.740
Two minutes, set a timer,

00:30:09.740 --> 00:30:11.910
everybody's in the doc dropping ideas.

00:30:11.910 --> 00:30:14.010
And what's amazing is
you can see sometimes

00:30:14.010 --> 00:30:18.320
like an idea that was typed or added

00:30:18.320 --> 00:30:19.520
by somebody who would normally be

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:20.900
a quietest voice, is getting like

00:30:20.900 --> 00:30:24.210
a pile of emoji reactions from
everyone else in the team,

00:30:24.210 --> 00:30:25.440
but they didn't have to fight

00:30:25.440 --> 00:30:27.253
to get that word in edgewise.

00:30:28.630 --> 00:30:30.690
Another thing that I
did, especially early on

00:30:30.690 --> 00:30:33.130
when I was managing a smaller team

00:30:33.130 --> 00:30:35.660
was when there were
really tough trade-offs,

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:37.240
instead of people going in circles

00:30:37.240 --> 00:30:38.160
on the conversation, I'd say,

00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:39.500
let's just make a pros/cons table,

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:41.520
we're all gonna fill this
table in together quietly

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:43.550
and then we'll look at the
pros and cons together.

00:30:43.550 --> 00:30:45.330
So that it doesn't turn to this like,

00:30:45.330 --> 00:30:47.170
who's more skilled at debate,

00:30:47.170 --> 00:30:50.140
and we're just looking at the
reasons on the page together.

00:30:50.140 --> 00:30:51.525
Yeah, stuff like that.

00:30:51.525 --> 00:30:53.510
But I would say it's pretty
constant and deliberate,

00:30:53.510 --> 00:30:56.760
and so it just takes more brain vitamins.

00:30:56.760 --> 00:30:59.250
- Yeah, just to kind of, you know, yeah.

00:30:59.250 --> 00:31:01.880
So when May-Li is tired
at the end of the day,

00:31:01.880 --> 00:31:03.950
it's because she's been
thinking doubly hard

00:31:03.950 --> 00:31:05.460
about leadership.
- Yeah, everything takes

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:06.303
two layers of thought.
- That's right.

00:31:06.303 --> 00:31:07.810
- It's like, okay, here's the thing,

00:31:07.810 --> 00:31:09.200
now let me do the double check on it.

00:31:09.200 --> 00:31:11.270
- Yeah, that sounds great.

00:31:11.270 --> 00:31:12.103
I think kind of one of things

00:31:12.103 --> 00:31:13.200
that you just said, May-Li,

00:31:13.200 --> 00:31:16.283
was about making sure people's
voices are represented.

00:31:17.855 --> 00:31:19.790
And, I guess, because you two

00:31:19.790 --> 00:31:21.770
are kind of in senior leadership roles,

00:31:21.770 --> 00:31:23.890
you often are in meetings or in rooms

00:31:23.890 --> 00:31:26.500
where many other employees may not be.

00:31:26.500 --> 00:31:29.850
How is it that you are kind of thinking

00:31:29.850 --> 00:31:31.340
of those who aren't in the room

00:31:31.340 --> 00:31:32.970
when you are in these big meetings?

00:31:32.970 --> 00:31:34.370
Like how do you make sure you're bringing

00:31:34.370 --> 00:31:36.513
along voices who may not usually be heard?

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:39.440
- Yeah, I mean, that's a great question.

00:31:39.440 --> 00:31:42.520
Well, what all need to be aware of,

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:44.360
what I remind myself to
be aware of all the time

00:31:44.360 --> 00:31:46.948
is we have constituents,
so to speak, right?

00:31:46.948 --> 00:31:50.160
So if I'm in a meeting, I'm
not representing myself,

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:52.540
like 99.9% of the time, right?

00:31:52.540 --> 00:31:54.653
And so I'm representing others.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:58.280
Yeah, I think that that's an important

00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:01.040
sort of general consciousness
to take into things,

00:32:01.040 --> 00:32:03.270
so that when we discuss things

00:32:03.270 --> 00:32:05.220
about our company, for example,

00:32:05.220 --> 00:32:07.120
in our senior leadership team meeting,

00:32:08.587 --> 00:32:10.790
the lens for us always
is we're representing

00:32:10.790 --> 00:32:14.910
our function here, so what
do my folks feel about this?

00:32:14.910 --> 00:32:17.423
What would work best for my folks?

00:32:18.547 --> 00:32:19.703
What have I heard?

00:32:21.640 --> 00:32:23.500
It's a lot about listening.

00:32:23.500 --> 00:32:24.590
It's a lot about listening,

00:32:24.590 --> 00:32:27.200
which kinda gets back to
the voices not being heard.

00:32:27.200 --> 00:32:28.470
There's so much you can pick up

00:32:28.470 --> 00:32:31.610
in just watching body
language and watching people,

00:32:31.610 --> 00:32:34.200
and you can tell when
somebody has something to say.

00:32:34.200 --> 00:32:36.420
I mean, a classic thing that we can do

00:32:36.420 --> 00:32:38.460
to help with that is to say,

00:32:38.460 --> 00:32:40.840
oh, it looks like maybe
you have something to say.

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:42.610
I mean, and you have to
find out ahead of time

00:32:42.610 --> 00:32:44.400
who's comfortable with that and who isn't,

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:45.460
but there are plenty of people

00:32:45.460 --> 00:32:46.490
who are comfortable with that,

00:32:46.490 --> 00:32:48.600
they just need that extra little push

00:32:48.600 --> 00:32:51.540
to be asked to join the conversation.

00:32:51.540 --> 00:32:54.220
- Yeah, that last thing
is really important,

00:32:54.220 --> 00:32:58.823
I think, because it starts so early.

00:32:59.850 --> 00:33:01.420
I've watched this in classrooms too,

00:33:01.420 --> 00:33:04.210
who feels like they can speak up

00:33:04.210 --> 00:33:06.680
and who doesn't feel
like they can speak up.

00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:09.100
And so it isn't enough to just say like,

00:33:09.100 --> 00:33:12.760
the door's open, like you
also have to invite people in.

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:14.660
And being mindful of all of that,

00:33:14.660 --> 00:33:17.070
being super mindful of my own reactions,

00:33:17.070 --> 00:33:18.640
not necessarily expecting somebody

00:33:18.640 --> 00:33:22.008
to have a perfectly
formulated thought, coming in.

00:33:22.008 --> 00:33:22.841
- [Rachel] Right.

00:33:22.841 --> 00:33:23.900
- I've definitely told people like, look,

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:27.060
I just need the data, it's like what

00:33:27.060 --> 00:33:27.893
we were talking about earlier,

00:33:27.893 --> 00:33:30.200
I just wanna learn so that I can

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:32.690
fix anything that needs fixing,

00:33:32.690 --> 00:33:34.840
and I can't do that if
I don't have the data.

00:33:34.840 --> 00:33:36.170
And the way that I don't get data

00:33:36.170 --> 00:33:38.380
is if I make myself unapproachable,

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:40.580
or if there aren't other,
or whether it's me,

00:33:40.580 --> 00:33:41.800
or if there aren't other routes

00:33:41.800 --> 00:33:43.780
for that information to get to me.

00:33:43.780 --> 00:33:45.893
So sometimes I tell people like, look,

00:33:46.780 --> 00:33:49.810
it's okay if you don't have
this thoughtfully formulated,

00:33:49.810 --> 00:33:51.240
just tell me what you can,

00:33:51.240 --> 00:33:53.520
and I'm gonna help you tease it apart.

00:33:53.520 --> 00:33:54.850
- [Rachel] Yeah, that
sounds really great too.

00:33:54.850 --> 00:33:56.447
- Yeah.

00:33:56.447 --> 00:33:57.463
- And then, I guess,

00:33:58.690 --> 00:33:59.980
I'm trying to figure out the best way

00:33:59.980 --> 00:34:01.630
to formulate this question, when,

00:34:03.460 --> 00:34:05.450
I always feel like when women are in lead

00:34:05.450 --> 00:34:06.750
or there are women around,

00:34:07.623 --> 00:34:09.960
it is a bit of more inclusive,

00:34:09.960 --> 00:34:13.960
it is a more thoughtful
work environment, right?

00:34:13.960 --> 00:34:17.903
What is the opposite of that, right?

