I worked throughout, but
didn't really progress upward.

00:40:54.230 --> 00:40:57.540
It was more outward in
different fields and roles.

00:40:57.540 --> 00:41:01.260
I love what I do now and I'm
finally enjoying my work,

00:41:01.260 --> 00:41:03.040
even though the path was wayward.

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:05.620
However, I want to progress upward now.

00:41:05.620 --> 00:41:06.930
Any advice?

00:41:06.930 --> 00:41:08.780
And this is a question from Facebook.

00:41:13.700 --> 00:41:15.040
- It's interesting 'cause we both

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:16.940
talked about how, in meandering.

00:41:16.940 --> 00:41:19.077
- Not focusing on upward so much,

00:41:19.077 --> 00:41:21.873
just sort of meandering
through the outward.

00:41:22.860 --> 00:41:24.303
- Yeah, I think to that question,

00:41:24.303 --> 00:41:27.960
I think people feel a lot of pressure

00:41:27.960 --> 00:41:30.290
to sort of do A plus B equals C,

00:41:30.290 --> 00:41:32.816
and that's how I feel successful,

00:41:32.816 --> 00:41:36.610
and that's how I build a good life.

00:41:36.610 --> 00:41:39.040
And I think part of it is

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:40.213
letting people know that it's okay

00:41:40.213 --> 00:41:43.270
that it doesn't look like A plus B plus C.

00:41:43.270 --> 00:41:45.550
That it can look like all kinds of things.

00:41:45.550 --> 00:41:48.283
- 'Cause the way that I see it is,

00:41:49.120 --> 00:41:51.250
the way I see it and I've always seen it

00:41:51.250 --> 00:41:55.430
is that you have to decide for yourself

00:41:55.430 --> 00:41:58.210
what you revere, like what you look up to.

00:41:58.210 --> 00:42:02.950
And that doesn't have to be what

00:42:02.950 --> 00:42:05.010
is dictated by a status quo either.

00:42:05.010 --> 00:42:06.710
And some of the people
that you most admire

00:42:06.710 --> 00:42:08.570
might be somebody who aren't in

00:42:09.630 --> 00:42:11.440
some sort of position of leadership.

00:42:11.440 --> 00:42:13.260
They might be somebody
who's doing something else

00:42:13.260 --> 00:42:14.190
that you find amazing,

00:42:14.190 --> 00:42:17.420
and that's totally cool and awesome.

00:42:17.420 --> 00:42:20.700
So I just feel like if this person

00:42:20.700 --> 00:42:22.900
is interested in getting into management,

00:42:22.900 --> 00:42:25.040
then to treat that as a skill

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:26.810
because it's a different skill.

00:42:26.810 --> 00:42:31.160
And obviously, managing a
particular area is great,

00:42:31.160 --> 00:42:34.030
it's better if you have
craft in that area,

00:42:34.030 --> 00:42:35.710
but it is a different
thing to learn altogether.

00:42:35.710 --> 00:42:37.373
It's a totally different skillset.

00:42:37.373 --> 00:42:38.206
- [Rachel] Right.

00:42:38.206 --> 00:42:39.039
- And so treating it that way

00:42:39.039 --> 00:42:40.970
and being interested in
that I think helps a lot,

00:42:40.970 --> 00:42:44.330
recognizing that it's a totally
different thing to learn.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:45.450
- Yeah--

00:42:45.450 --> 00:42:46.640
- And I don't think of it as up,

00:42:46.640 --> 00:42:48.400
I think of it as just, it's another thing.

00:42:48.400 --> 00:42:51.373
There's like many paths,
and that's one path.

00:42:51.373 --> 00:42:53.370
- Yeah, but to get back to it,

00:42:53.370 --> 00:42:56.130
I don't want to sort of poo-poo the fact

00:42:56.130 --> 00:42:58.190
that someone wants to grow upward--

00:42:58.190 --> 00:42:59.640
- No, that's true.
- So just kind of,

00:42:59.640 --> 00:43:02.030
because I know we both kind of think of it

00:43:02.030 --> 00:43:03.970
in a similar way that's
a little bit different,

00:43:03.970 --> 00:43:06.230
but I think, sure, you have a goal,

00:43:06.230 --> 00:43:09.110
and you want to grow kind of upward

00:43:09.110 --> 00:43:12.220
in more senior roles, titles, let's say,

00:43:12.220 --> 00:43:16.170
I think some ideas are
you find mentors, right?

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:18.630
Sign somebody up who's going to say,

00:43:18.630 --> 00:43:20.210
I'll be working with you all the time,

00:43:20.210 --> 00:43:21.920
and if that's your goal,
I'm gonna help you.

00:43:21.920 --> 00:43:23.730
And they will then take it apart for you,

00:43:23.730 --> 00:43:24.780
help you take it apart.

00:43:24.780 --> 00:43:26.640
Here are skills, right, that I've observed

00:43:26.640 --> 00:43:27.473
when you're telling me,

00:43:27.473 --> 00:43:28.980
these are the things we could work on.

00:43:28.980 --> 00:43:31.110
So there is a way to get there.

00:43:31.110 --> 00:43:32.870
I don't wanna make light of ambition

00:43:32.870 --> 00:43:36.259
for anybody because that's yours

00:43:36.259 --> 00:43:39.470
and going forward.

00:43:39.470 --> 00:43:42.180
So I would say getting help from others

00:43:42.180 --> 00:43:43.700
is probably a great tool.

00:43:43.700 --> 00:43:45.350
- I think the other
thing that comes to mind

00:43:45.350 --> 00:43:49.500
is also like putting
yourself in the shoes,

00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:53.900
the empathetic shoes of the
person who would hire you

00:43:53.900 --> 00:43:56.670
or the person who would
ask you to do this work

00:43:56.670 --> 00:43:59.720
and get an idea of like what
problems are you solving,

00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:02.310
like what is it that they're looking for.

00:44:02.310 --> 00:44:03.730
So if you have an idea that you're like,

00:44:03.730 --> 00:44:06.590
okay, well, I'm at this organization,

00:44:06.590 --> 00:44:07.870
there's this spot open,

00:44:07.870 --> 00:44:10.640
here's the big problems
that I see right now,

00:44:10.640 --> 00:44:11.820
and I would imagine they need me

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:13.450
to jump in and do X, Y, and Z.

00:44:13.450 --> 00:44:15.640
Just try and get that vantage point

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:17.750
because then you can start building up

00:44:17.750 --> 00:44:19.380
the skill in a really empathic way

00:44:19.380 --> 00:44:22.440
that plugs into like your
mentors or whoever it is,

00:44:22.440 --> 00:44:25.230
and you can say like, look,
I know that you're probably

00:44:25.230 --> 00:44:26.970
facing these challenges, is that correct?

00:44:26.970 --> 00:44:27.803
- [Rachel] Right, exactly.

00:44:27.803 --> 00:44:29.510
- Okay, cool, so here are the things

00:44:29.510 --> 00:44:31.130
that I feel like are additive,

00:44:31.130 --> 00:44:33.780
instead of it being sort
of from you outward.

00:44:33.780 --> 00:44:35.640
It's kind of like a design problem.

00:44:35.640 --> 00:44:36.693
- [Rachel] Yeah, exactly.

00:44:36.693 --> 00:44:38.283
- You're like, okay, what
does this person need?

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:21.760
Explicit about saying things like,

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:23.720
okay, look, if this is the total trade-off

00:45:23.720 --> 00:45:24.860
and there isn't a right answer,

00:45:24.860 --> 00:45:25.910
I'm gonna just say that.

00:45:25.910 --> 00:45:27.967
I'm not gonna just pretend that there's

00:45:27.967 --> 00:45:29.730
always a direction that I see

00:45:29.730 --> 00:45:33.363
because I magically see all
directions of everything.

00:45:34.290 --> 00:45:35.980
And then I would just speak to that meta

00:45:35.980 --> 00:45:38.840
and say like, I know that's
a style, that's not my style.

00:45:38.840 --> 00:45:41.480
And so I think from all sides,

00:45:41.480 --> 00:45:45.020
there's kind of an image of
what leadership looks like,

00:45:45.020 --> 00:45:46.670
whether you're the person who's accepting

00:45:46.670 --> 00:45:47.950
somebody as your leader,

00:45:47.950 --> 00:45:49.870
or if you're somebody
who's promoting somebody

00:45:49.870 --> 00:45:51.573
into a position of leadership.

00:45:53.625 --> 00:45:55.140
And I think it can be hard sometimes

00:45:55.140 --> 00:45:56.740
for people to look past that

00:45:56.740 --> 00:45:58.010
and see different kinds of cues

00:45:58.010 --> 00:45:59.680
for different styles of leaders.

